2.3.2. BDC isolation from PET bottles
After removing the bottle caps and labels, the bottles were sliced into 1 × 1 cm2 flakes, rinsed with distilled water, and dried in an oven. In a 10 M NaOH solution, 100 g of cutting flasks were added, and the solution was vigorously stirred at 100 °C for 10 h
[29]
,
[35]
. After cooling to room temperature to 5 °C by an ice bath, the solution was treated with concentrated sulfuric acid until pH= 2. The white precipitate was filtered and washed with distilled water many times until the aqueous filtrate was free from SO42- ions. The residue was then dried in an oven overnight at 100 °C to yield DBC as a white powder at a low cost (
Table S1
